        </p>

        <h3>Factors Behind the 2026 Healthcare Priority</h3>
        <ul class="marker:text-sky-600">
          <li>
            <strong>Aging Population:</strong> BC's population is aging rapidly, with seniors (65+) expected to comprise over 25% of residents by 2030. This demographic shift dramatically increases demand for healthcare services, particularly in long-term care and chronic disease management.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Workforce Retirements:</strong> Many experienced healthcare workers are reaching retirement age. The province estimates that over 15% of current nurses and 20% of physicians will retire within the next five years.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Rural and Remote Gaps:</strong> Northern and Interior regions face severe shortages, with some communities having no resident physicians. The government is prioritizing international recruitment to fill these gaps.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Post-Pandemic Recovery:</strong> Healthcare systems continue to recover from increased workloads and burnout-related resignations during recent years. Rebuilding capacity requires significant new recruitment.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>New Facility Openings:</strong> Several new hospitals and healthcare facilities are opening across BC, including expansions in Surrey, Burnaby, and the Interior, creating thousands of new positions.
          </li>
        </ul>

