        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <h3>Can I apply if I work for a private hospital?</h3>
        <p>
          Private hospitals that are not affiliated with a public health
          authority typically do not qualify for the Health Authority stream.
          However, you may still be eligible under the regular Skilled Worker
          stream with a higher score requirement.
        </p>

        <h3>What if I am still waiting for my nursing license?</h3>
        <p>
          You can register in SIRS and receive an invitation while your license
          is pending. However, you must have your license before your health
          authority can finalize your job offer and before you can begin working.
        </p>

        <h3>Do I need Canadian work experience?</h3>
        <p>
          Not necessarily. If you have a job offer from a public health
          authority and meet other requirements, you may qualify without prior
          Canadian experience. This is one of the key advantages of the Health Authority stream.
        </p>

        <h3>What language score do I need?</h3>
        <p>
          Most healthcare regulatory bodies require CLB 7 or higher for
          registration. BC PNP itself may accept lower scores, but your
          professional regulator's requirements will apply. Check with your specific regulatory body for exact requirements.
        </p>

        <h3>Can my family immigrate with me?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes, your spouse/common-law partner and dependent children can be included in your permanent residence application. They will receive PR status at the same time as you.
        </p>

        <h3>What happens if my application is refused?</h3>
        <p>
          If your BC PNP application is refused, you will receive a letter explaining the reasons. You may be able to address the issues and reapply. Common reasons for refusal include incomplete documentation, ineligible job offer, or failure to meet minimum requirements.
